<text top="41" left="55" width="177" height="10" font="font0" id="p1_t1" reading_order_no="0" segment_no="0" tag_type="title">Cell Communication and Signaling 2005, 3 :6<i>Cell Communication and Signaling</i></text>
<text top="41" left="388" width="166" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t2" reading_order_no="1" segment_no="1" tag_type="text">http://www.biosignaling.com/content/3/1/6</text>
<text top="756" left="508" width="46" height="10" font="font1" id="p1_t3" reading_order_no="106" segment_no="16" tag_type="text">Page 5 of 8<b>3</b></text>
<text top="769" left="432" width="122" height="8" font="font3" id="p1_t4" reading_order_no="107" segment_no="17" tag_type="text">(page number not for citation purposes)</text>
<text top="87" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font4" id="p1_t5" reading_order_no="2" segment_no="2" tag_type="title">Anti-inflammatory treatment and expression of ccn1 and</text>
<text top="99" left="55" width="46" height="9" font="font5" id="p1_t6" reading_order_no="3" segment_no="2" tag_type="title">ccn2 genes</text>
<text top="110" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t7" reading_order_no="4" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">Glucocorticoids are known to possess strong anti-inflam-<i>(page number not for citation purposes)</i></text>
<text top="122" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t8" reading_order_no="5" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">matory effects and also to be involved in the control of<i><b>Anti-inflammatory treatment and expression of </b></i></text>
<text top="134" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t9" reading_order_no="6" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">cartilage metabolism [21]. Particularly, the effectiveness<b>ccn1 </b></text>
<text top="145" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t10" reading_order_no="7" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">of glucocorticoids on RA symptom is so prominent that it<i><b>and </b></i></text>
<text top="157" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t11" reading_order_no="8" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">is frequently applied clinically, despite its adverse sys-<b>ccn2 </b></text>
<text top="169" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t12" reading_order_no="9" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">temic effects. It is already known that ccn2 gene expression<i><b>genes</b></i></text>
<text top="181" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t13" reading_order_no="10" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">is induced by glucocorticoids in chondrocytic cells as well</text>
<text top="192" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t14" reading_order_no="11" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">as in fibroblasts [22,23]. In contrast, molecular interac-</text>
<text top="204" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t15" reading_order_no="12" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">tion between glucocorticoids and ccn1 gene in chondro-<a href="">lism [21]. Partic</a>ularly, the effectiveness</text>
<text top="216" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t16" reading_order_no="13" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">cytes has not been investigated. Thus, we performed</text>
<text top="228" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t17" reading_order_no="14" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">Northern blot analysis, as well as the real-time RT-PCR</text>
<text top="239" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t18" reading_order_no="15" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">quantification to estimate the effects of glucocorticoids on</text>
<text top="251" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font7" id="p1_t19" reading_order_no="16" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">ccn1 and ccn2 gene expression. When HCS-2/8 cells were<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="263" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t20" reading_order_no="17" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">treated with 50 nM dexamethasone for 2.5 – 5 hours and</text>
<text top="275" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t21" reading_order_no="18" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">then examined by real-time PCR, ccn2 mRNA was induced</text>
<text top="286" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t22" reading_order_no="19" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">by 1.8 to 2.3 fold, and ccn1 mRNA was similarly induced<a href="">22,23]</a>. In contrast, molecular interac-</text>
<text top="298" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t23" reading_order_no="20" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">by 1.5 to 1.9 fold up to 5 h (Fig. 3A). The results obtained</text>
<text top="310" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t24" reading_order_no="21" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">by Northern blot analysis were quite similar to the PCR<i>ccn1 </i></text>
<text top="322" left="55" width="59" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t25" reading_order_no="22" segment_no="4" tag_type="text">ones (Fig 3B).</text>
<text top="345" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t26" reading_order_no="23" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">As a control experiment, we carried out similar analysis</text>
<text top="354" left="55" width="241" height="13" font="font6" id="p1_t27" reading_order_no="24" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">with 17 β -estradiol, which is another steroid hormone and</text>
<text top="369" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t28" reading_order_no="25" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">is also one of the regulators to maintain the homeostasis</text>
<text top="380" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t29" reading_order_no="26" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">of connective tissue. However, treatment of HCS-2/8 cells<i>ccn1 </i></text>
<text top="392" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t30" reading_order_no="27" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">with 10 nM estrogen for 1 – 24 hours resulted in no sig-</text>
<text top="404" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t31" reading_order_no="28" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">nificant change in ccn1 and ccn2 mRNA expression levels.<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="416" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t32" reading_order_no="29" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">In fact, no effects were observed even up to the concentra-</text>
<text top="427" left="55" width="143" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t33" reading_order_no="30" segment_no="5" tag_type="text">tion of 100 nM (data not shown).</text>
<text top="451" left="55" width="53" height="10" font="font9" id="p1_t34" reading_order_no="31" segment_no="6" tag_type="title">Discussion</text>
<text top="463" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t35" reading_order_no="32" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">In this study, we comparatively analyzed the expression<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="474" left="55" width="242" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t36" reading_order_no="33" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">profiles of ccn1 and ccn2 , while simulating the course of</text>
<text top="486" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t37" reading_order_no="34" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">arthritis; i.e., inflammation, tissue regeneration and anti-</text>
<text top="498" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t38" reading_order_no="35" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">inflammatory treatment, utilizing a human chondrocytic<i>ccn1 </i></text>
<text top="510" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t39" reading_order_no="36" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">HCS-2/8. In advance to the evaluation, we established a</text>
<text top="521" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t40" reading_order_no="37" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">real-time PCR quantification method by using a LightCy-<a href="">ig. 3A</a>). The results obtained</text>
<text top="533" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t41" reading_order_no="38" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">cler system. In view of the data provided for sensitivity,</text>
<text top="545" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t42" reading_order_no="39" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">linearity, and reproducibility, this assay system accurately<a href="">es (Fig 3B</a>).</text>
<text top="557" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t43" reading_order_no="40" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">allowed the discriminating quantification of these</text>
<text top="568" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t44" reading_order_no="41" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">mRNAs from the same gene family. The total reliability of</text>
<text top="580" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t45" reading_order_no="42" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">this system was evident, as represented by the facts that</text>
<text top="592" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t46" reading_order_no="43" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">every specific primer set produced distinct and specific</text>
<text top="604" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t47" reading_order_no="44" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">PCR products (Fig. 1) and quantitative results were com-</text>
<text top="615" left="55" width="212" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t48" reading_order_no="45" segment_no="8" tag_type="text">parable to those of Northern blot analysis (Fig. 3).</text>
<text top="639" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t49" reading_order_no="46" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">The involvement of CCN2 in arthritic diseases has been</text>
<text top="651" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t50" reading_order_no="47" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">indicated. In fact, expression of ccn2 gene in clinical cases</text>
<text top="662" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t51" reading_order_no="48" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">was reported [3]. Also in an experimental OA model, dis-<i>ccn1 </i></text>
<text top="674" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t52" reading_order_no="49" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">tinct induction of ccn2 gene expression was observed.</text>
<text top="686" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t53" reading_order_no="50" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">These findings are regarded as a regenerative response of<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="698" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t54" reading_order_no="51" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">damaged cartilage, since exogenously applied CCN2 was</text>
<text top="709" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t55" reading_order_no="52" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">proven to be effective in cartilage regeneration. In rat</text>
<text top="721" left="55" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t56" reading_order_no="53" segment_no="14" tag_type="text">models, CCN2 captured in collagen hydrogel to allow</text>
<text top="87" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t57" reading_order_no="54" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">gradual release of this factor efficiently promoted the<b>Discussion</b></text>
<text top="98" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t58" reading_order_no="55" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">regeneration of full-thickness cartilage defect and experi-</text>
<text top="110" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t59" reading_order_no="56" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">mentally induced OA cartilage [2]. Therefore, expression</text>
<text top="122" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t60" reading_order_no="57" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">profile of ccn2 in chondrocytes along the time course of<i>ccn1 </i></text>
<text top="134" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t61" reading_order_no="58" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">inflammation is thought to represent the proper gene reg-</text>
<text top="145" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t62" reading_order_no="59" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">ulation to provide a regenerative molecule during arthri-<i>ccn2</i></text>
<text top="157" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t63" reading_order_no="60" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">tis, and thus itself is worth investigated. More</text>
<text top="169" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t64" reading_order_no="61" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">interestingly, ccn1 gene expression exactly followed the</text>
<text top="181" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t65" reading_order_no="62" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">fluctuation pattern of ccn2 gene expression upon any kind</text>
<text top="192" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t66" reading_order_no="63" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">of stimulation tested. These results clearly indicate that</text>
<text top="204" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t67" reading_order_no="64" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">not only CCN2, but also CCN1 may be provided as a</text>
<text top="216" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t68" reading_order_no="65" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">regenerative molecule in arthritis. This hypothesis is sup-</text>
<text top="228" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t69" reading_order_no="66" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">ported by a number of their functional similarities.</text>
<text top="239" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t70" reading_order_no="67" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">Indeed, these factors are associated with the ECM, stimu-</text>
<text top="251" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t71" reading_order_no="68" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">late chemotaxis and promote proliferation of endothelial</text>
<text top="263" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t72" reading_order_no="69" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">cells and fibroblasts, and promote neovascularization and</text>
<text top="275" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t73" reading_order_no="70" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">chondrogenic differentiation [7-15,24]. Considering such</text>
<text top="286" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t74" reading_order_no="71" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">similarities and the concomitant fluctuation of gene<a href="">ts (Fig. 1) and q</a>uantitative results were com-</text>
<text top="298" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t75" reading_order_no="72" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">expression upon inflammation together, CCN1 is<a href="">is (Fig. 3).</a></text>
<text top="310" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t76" reading_order_no="73" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">expected to be one of the useful molecular tools to pro-</text>
<text top="322" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t77" reading_order_no="74" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">mote cartilage regeneration. In order to examine this</text>
<text top="333" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t78" reading_order_no="75" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">hypothesis, it is necessary to evaluate the regenerative<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="345" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t79" reading_order_no="76" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">potential of CCN1 protein in damaged articular cartilage,</text>
<text top="357" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t80" reading_order_no="77" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">as was examined with CCN2. In vivo evaluation of the<a href="">d [3]. Also in</a> an experimental OA model, dis-</text>
<text top="369" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t81" reading_order_no="78" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">expression of ccn1 upon OA and RA and the effects of</text>
<text top="380" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t82" reading_order_no="79" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">CCN1 protein on cartilage regeneration is currently in<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="392" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t83" reading_order_no="80" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">progress. Since all of the CCN family members are</text>
<text top="404" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t84" reading_order_no="81" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">thought to be mediators of multiple signaling molecules,</text>
<text top="416" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t85" reading_order_no="82" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">therapeutic utility of another member, such as CCN3/</text>
<text top="427" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t86" reading_order_no="83" segment_no="3" tag_type="text">NOV is also expected and obviously, need to be explored.</text>
<text top="451" left="313" width="56" height="10" font="font9" id="p1_t87" reading_order_no="84" segment_no="7" tag_type="title">Conclusion</text>
<text top="463" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font7" id="p1_t88" reading_order_no="85" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">In vitro simulation of arthritis with a human chondrocytic</text>
<text top="474" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t89" reading_order_no="86" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">cell line revealed the same response pattern of ccn1 as that</text>
<text top="486" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t90" reading_order_no="87" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">of ccn2 , which is known as a regenerative mediator in car-<a href=""> cartilage [2]</a>. Therefore, expression</text>
<text top="498" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t91" reading_order_no="88" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">tilage repair. Together with similar functionalities of</text>
<text top="510" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t92" reading_order_no="89" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">CCN1 and CCN2 in mesenchymal tissues, these results<i>ccn2 </i></text>
<text top="521" left="313" width="241" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t93" reading_order_no="90" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">suggest possible utility of CCN1 in regenerative therapy of</text>
<text top="533" left="313" width="131" height="9" font="font6" id="p1_t94" reading_order_no="91" segment_no="9" tag_type="text">damaged mesenchymal tissues.</text>
